[src:css-object-model/api-cssrule] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:css-object-model/api-cssrule] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:css-object-model/api-cssrule] The **`CSSRule`** interface represents a single CSS rule.
[src:css-object-model/api-cssrule] There are several types of rules which inherit properties from `CSSRule`.
[src:css-object-model/api-cssrule] The `CSSRule` interface specifies the properties common to all rules, while properties unique to specific rule types are specified in the more specialized interfaces for those rules' respective types.
[src:css-object-model/api-cssrule] Represents the textual representation of the rule, e.g., `"h1,h2 { font-size: 16pt }"` or `"@import 'url'"`.
[src:css-object-model/api-cssrule] To access or modify parts of the rule (e.g., the value of "font-size" in the example) use the properties on the specialized interface for the rule's type (see above).
[src:css-object-model/api-cssrule] Returns the containing rule, otherwise `null`.
[src:css-object-model/api-cssrule] E.g. if this rule is a style rule inside an `@media` block, the parent rule would be that `CSSMediaRule`.
[src:css-object-model/api-cssrule] Returns one of the Type constants to determine which type of rule is represented.
[src:css-object-model/api-cssrule] References to a `CSSRule` may be obtained by looking at a `CSSStyleSheet`'s `cssRules` list.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is designed to enable the separation of content and presentation, including layout, colors, and fonts.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Separation of formatting and content also makes it feasible to present the same markup page in different styles for different rendering methods, such as on-screen, in print, by voice (via speech-based browser or screen reader), and on Braille-based tactile devices.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also has rules for alternative formatting if the content is accessed on a mobile device.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] The name *cascading* comes from the specified priority scheme to determine which declaration applies if more than one declaration of a property match a particular element.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] This cascading priority scheme is predictable.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] The CSS specifications are maintained by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Internet media type (MIME type) `text/css` is registered for use with CSS by RFC 2318 (March 1998).
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C operates a free CSS validation service for CSS documents.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] In addition to HTML, other markup languages support the use of CSS including XHTML, plain XML, SVG, and XUL.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] CSS is also used in the GTK widget toolkit.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] CSS has a simple syntax and uses a number of English keywords to specify the names of various style properties.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] A style sheet consists of a list of *rules*.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Each rule or rule-set consists of one or more *selectors*, and a *declaration block*.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] In CSS, *selectors* declare which part of the markup a style applies to by matching tags and attributes in the markup itself.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Classes and IDs are case-sensitive, start with letters, and can include alphanumeric characters, hyphens, and underscores.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] A class may apply to any number of instances of any element.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] An ID may only be applied to a single element.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] One example of a widely used pseudo-class is `:hover`, which identifies content only when the user "points to" the visible element, usually by holding the mouse cursor over it.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] It is appended to a selector as in `a:hover` or `#elementid:hover`.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] A pseudo-class classifies document elements, such as `:link` or `:visited`, whereas a *pseudo-element* makes a selection that may consist of partial elements, such as `::first-line` or `::first-letter`.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Note the distinction between the double-colon notation used for pseudo-elements and the single-colon notation used for pseudo-classes.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Multiple simple selectors may be joined using combinators to specify elements by location, element type, id, class, or any combination thereof.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] The order of the selectors is important.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] For example, `div .myClass {color: red;}` applies to all elements of class myClass that are inside div elements, whereas `.myClass div {color: red;}` applies to all div elements that are inside elements of class myClass.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] This is not to be confused with concatenated identifiers such as `div.myClass {color: red;}` which applies to div elements of class myClass.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] The following table provides a summary of selector syntax indicating usage and the version of CSS that introduced it.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] A declaration block consists of a pair of braces (`{}`) enclosing a semicolon-separated list of *declarations*.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Each declaration itself consists of a *property*, a colon (`:`), and a *value*.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Optional white-space may be around the declaration block, declarations, colons, and semi-colons for readability.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Properties are specified in the CSS standard.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Each property has a set of possible values.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Some properties can affect any type of element, and others apply only to particular groups of elements.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Values may be keywords, such as "center" or "inherit", or numerical values, such as `200px` (200 pixels), `50vw` (50 percent of the viewport width) or 80% (80 percent of the parent element's width).
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Color values can be specified with keywords (e.g.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] `rgb(255, 0, 0)`), RGBA values that specify both color and alpha transparency (e.g.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Non-zero numeric values representing linear measures must include a length unit, which is either an alphabetic code or abbreviation, as in `200px` or `50vw`; or a percentage sign, as in `80%`.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] These eight units were a feature of CSS 1 and retained in all subsequent revisions.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] The proposed CSS Values and Units Module Level 3 will, if adopted as a W3C Recommendation, provide seven further length units: `ch`; `Q`; `rem`; `vh`; `vmax`; `vmin`; and `vw`.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, nearly all presentational attributes of HTML documents were contained within the HTML markup.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] That is, all font colors, background styles, element alignments, borders, and sizes had to be explicitly described (often repeatedly) within the HTML.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] CSS lets authors move much of that information to another file, the style sheet, resulting in considerably simpler HTML.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] And additionally, as more and more devices are able to access responsive web pages, different screen sizes and layouts begin to appear.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Customizing a website for each device size is costly and increasingly difficult.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] The modular nature of CSS means that styles can be reused in different parts of a site or even across sites, promoting consistency and efficiency.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] For example, headings (`h1` elements), sub-headings (`h2`), sub-sub-headings (`h3`), etc., are defined structurally using HTML.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] In print and on the screen, choice of font, size, color and emphasis for these elements is *presentational*.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] Before CSS, document authors who wanted to assign such typographic characteristics to, say, all `h2` headings had to repeat HTML presentational markup for each occurrence of that heading type.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] This made documents more complex, larger, and more error-prone and difficult to maintain.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] CSS allows the separation of presentation from structure.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] CSS can define color, font, text alignment, size, borders, spacing, layout and many other typographic characteristics, and can do so independently for on-screen and printed views.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] CSS also defines non-visual styles, such as reading speed and emphasis for aural text readers.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] The W3C has now deprecated the use of all presentational HTML markup.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] The advantages of this may not be immediately clear but the power of CSS becomes more apparent when the style properties are placed in an internal style element or, even better, an external CSS file.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] All `h1` elements in the document will then automatically become red without requiring any explicit code.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] rather than by laboriously going through the document and changing the color for each individual `h1` element.
[src:css-object-model/cascading-style-sheets] This further decouples the styling from the HTML document and makes it possible to restyle multiple documents by simply editing a shared external CSS file.
[src:css-object-model/css-object-model] The **CSS Object Model** is a set of APIs allowing the manipulation of CSS from JavaScript.
[src:css-object-model/css-object-model] It is much like the DOM, but for the CSS rather than the HTML.
[src:css-object-model/css-object-model] It allows users to read and modify CSS style dynamically.
[src:css-object-model/css-object-model] The values of CSS are represented untyped, that is using `String` objects.
[src:css-object-model/css-object-model] Several other interfaces are also extended by the CSSOM-related specifications: `Document`, `Window`, `Element`, `HTMLElement`, `HTMLImageElement`, `Range`, `MouseEvent`, and `SVGElement`.
[src:css-object-model/css-object-model] All these features have been added little by little over the years to the different browsers: it was a quite complex process that can't be summarized in a simple table.
[src:css-object-model/css-object-model] Please refer to the specific interfaces for its availability.
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] The interface exposes style information and various style-related methods and properties.
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] For example, it provides `getPropertyValue()` for getting the value of a dash-named CSS property, such as `border-top`, which can't be directly accessed using dot notation because of the hyphens in its name.
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] Textual representation of the declaration block, if and only if it is exposed via `HTMLElement.style`.
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] Setting this attribute changes the inline style.
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] If you want a text representation of a computed declaration block, you can get it with `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] Special alias for the `float` CSS property.
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] Dashed and camel-cased attributes for all supported CSS properties.
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] Returns the optional priority, "important".
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] Returns the property value given a property name.
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] Returns a CSS property name by its index, or the empty string if the index is out-of-bounds.
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] Removes a property from the CSS declaration block.
[src:css-object-model/cssstyledeclaration] Modifies an existing CSS property or creates a new CSS property in the declaration block.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] The **`CSSStyleSheet`** interface represents a single CSS stylesheet, and lets you inspect and modify the list of rules contained in the stylesheet.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] It inherits properties and methods from its parent, `StyleSheet`.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] A stylesheet consists of a collection of `CSSRule` objects representing each of the rules in the stylesheet.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] The rules are contained in a `CSSRuleList`, which can be obtained from the stylesheet's `cssRules` property.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] Another rule might be an *at-rule* such as `@import` or `@media`, and so forth.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] See the Obtaining a StyleSheet section for the various ways a `CSSStyleSheet` object can be obtained.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] A `CSSStyleSheet` object can also be directly constructed.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] The constructor, and the `CSSStyleSheet.replace()`, and `CSSStyleSheet.replaceSync()` methods are newer additions to the specification, enabling *Constructable Stylesheets*.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] To apply a `CSSStyleSheet` to a document or shadow root, assign it to the `Document.adoptedStyleSheets` or `ShadowRoot.adoptedStyleSheets` property, respectively.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] Returns a live `CSSRuleList` which maintains an up-to-date list of the `CSSRule` objects that comprise the stylesheet.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] If this stylesheet is imported into the document using an `@import` rule, the `ownerRule` property returns the corresponding `CSSImportRule`; otherwise, this property's value is `null`.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] Deletes the rule at the specified index into the stylesheet's rule list.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] Inserts a new rule at the specified position in the stylesheet, given the textual representation of the rule.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] Asynchronously replaces the content of the stylesheet and returns a `Promise` that resolves with the updated `CSSStyleSheet`.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] Synchronously replaces the content of the stylesheet.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] The `rules` property is functionally identical to the standard `cssRules` property; it returns a live `CSSRuleList` which maintains an up-to-date list of all of the rules in the style sheet.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] Adds a new rule to the stylesheet given the selector to which the style applies and the style block to apply to the matching elements.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] This differs from `insertRule()`, which takes the textual representation of the entire rule as a single string.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] Functionally identical to `deleteRule()`; removes the rule at the specified index from the stylesheet's rule list.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] A stylesheet is associated with at most one `Document`, which it applies to (unless disabled).
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] A list of `CSSStyleSheet` objects for a given document can be obtained using the `Document.styleSheets` property.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] A specific style sheet can also be accessed from its *owner* object (`Node` or `CSSImportRule`), if any.
[src:css-object-model/cssstylesheet] A `CSSStyleSheet` object is created and inserted into the document's `Document.styleSheets` list automatically by the browser, when a stylesheet is loaded for a document.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) is a cross-platform and language-independent API that treats an HTML or XML document as a tree structure wherein each node is an object representing a part of the document.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] The DOM represents a document with a logical tree.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Each branch of the tree ends in a node, and each node contains objects.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree; with them one can change the structure, style or content of a document.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Nodes can have event handlers (also known as event listeners) attached to them.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Once an event is triggered, the event handlers get executed.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] The principal standardization of the DOM was handled by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), which last developed a recommendation in 2004.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] WHATWG took over the development of the standard, publishing it as a living document.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] The W3C now publishes stable snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] JavaScript was released by Netscape Communications in 1995 within Netscape Navigator 2.0.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Netscape's competitor, Microsoft, released Internet Explorer 3.0 the following year with a reimplementation of JavaScript called JScript.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] JavaScript and JScript let web developers create web pages with client-side interactivity.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Legacy DOM was limited in the kinds of elements that could be accessed.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Form, link and image elements could be referenced with a hierarchical name that began with the root document object.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] A hierarchical name could make use of either the names or the sequential index of the traversed elements.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] For example, a form input element could be accessed as either `document.myForm.myInput` or `document.forms[0].elements[0]`.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] The Legacy DOM enabled client-side form validation and simple interface interactivity like creating tooltips.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] In 1997, Netscape and Microsoft released version 4.0 of Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer respectively, adding support for Dynamic HTML (DHTML) functionality enabling changes to a loaded HTML document.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] DHTML required extensions to the rudimentary document object that was available in the Legacy DOM implementations.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Although the Legacy DOM implementations were largely compatible since JScript was based on JavaScript, the DHTML DOM extensions were developed in parallel by each browser maker and remained incompatible.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] These versions of the DOM became known as the "Intermediate DOM".
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] After the standardization of ECMAScript, the W3C DOM Working Group began drafting a standard DOM specification.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] The completed specification, known as "DOM Level 1", became a W3C Recommendation in late 1998.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] By 2005, large parts of W3C DOM were well-supported by common ECMAScript-enabled browsers, including Internet Explorer 6 (from 2001), Opera, Safari and Gecko-based browsers (like Mozilla, Firefox, SeaMonkey and Camino).
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] The W3C DOM Working Group published its final recommendation and subsequently disbanded in 2004.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Development efforts migrated to the WHATWG, which continues to maintain a living standard.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] In 2009, the Web Applications group reorganized DOM activities at the W3C.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] In 2013, due to a lack of progress and the impending release of HTML5, the DOM Level 4 specification was reassigned to the HTML Working Group to expedite its completion.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Meanwhile, in 2015, the Web Applications group was disbanded and DOM stewardship passed to the Web Platform group.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Beginning with the publication of DOM Level 4 in 2015, the W3C creates new recommendations based on snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] To render a document such as a HTML page, most web browsers use an internal model similar to the DOM.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] The nodes of every document are organized in a tree structure, called the *DOM tree*, with the topmost node named as "Document object".
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] When an HTML page is rendered in browsers, the browser downloads the HTML into local memory and automatically parses it to display the page on screen.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] However, the DOM does not necessarily need to be represented as a tree, and some browsers have used other internal models.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] When a web page is loaded, the browser creates a Document Object Model of the page, which is an object oriented representation of an HTML document that acts as an interface between JavaScript and the document itself.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] A Document Object Model (DOM) tree is a hierarchical representation of an HTML or XML document.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] It consists of a root node, which is the document itself, and a series of child nodes that represent the elements, attributes, and text content of the document.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Each node in the tree has a parent node, except for the root node, and can have multiple child nodes.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Elements in an HTML or XML document are represented as nodes in the DOM tree.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Each element node has a tag name and attributes, and can contain other element nodes or text nodes as children.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Text content within an element is represented as a text node in the DOM tree.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Text nodes do not have attributes or child nodes and are therefore always leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] For example, the text content "My Website" in the title element and "Welcome" in the h1 element are both represented as text nodes.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Attributes of an element are represented as properties of the element node in the DOM tree.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] The DOM tree can be manipulated using JavaScript or other programming languages.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Common tasks include navigating the tree, adding, removing, and modifying nodes, and getting and setting the properties of nodes.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] The DOM API provides a set of methods and properties to perform these operations, such as `getElementById`, `createElement`, `appendChild`, and `innerHTML`.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Another way to create a DOM structure is using the innerHTML property to insert HTML code as a string, creating the elements and children in the process.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Another method is to use a JavaScript library or framework such as jQuery, AngularJS, React, Vue.js, Svelte, etc.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] These libraries provide an efficient way to create, manipulate and interact with the DOM.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] It is also possible to create a DOM structure from an XML or JSON data, using JavaScript methods to parse the data and create the nodes accordingly.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Creating a DOM structure does not necessarily mean that it will be displayed in the web page, it only exists in memory and should be appended to the document body or a specific container to be rendered.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] In summary, creating a DOM structure involves creating individual nodes and organizing them in a hierarchical structure using JavaScript or other programming languages, and it can be done using several methods depending on the use case and the developer's preference.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Because the DOM supports navigation in any direction (e.g., parent and previous sibling) and allows for arbitrary modifications, implementations typically buffer the document.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] However, a DOM need not originate in a serialized document at all, but can be created in place with the DOM API.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] And even before the idea of the DOM originated, there were implementations of equivalent structure with persistent disk representation and rapid access, for example DynaText's model disclosed in and various database approaches.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Web browsers rely on layout engines to parse HTML into a DOM.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Some layout engines, such as Trident/MSHTML, are associated primarily or exclusively with a particular browser, such as Internet Explorer.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] Others, including Blink, WebKit, and Gecko, are shared by a number of browsers, such as Google Chrome, Opera, Safari, and Firefox.
[src:css-object-model/document-object-model] The different layout engines implement the DOM standards to varying degrees of compliance.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] The **`Window.getComputedStyle()`** method returns a live read-only `CSSStyleProperties` object containing the resolved values of all CSS properties of an element, after applying active stylesheets and resolving any computation those values may contain.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] The `Element` for which to get the computed style.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] A string specifying the pseudo-element to match.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] A *live* `CSSStyleProperties` object, which updates automatically when the element's styles change.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] If the passed object is not an `Element` or the `pseudoElt` is not a valid pseudo-element selector or is `::part()` or `::slotted()`.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] The method returns a live read-only `CSSStyleProperties` object containing the resolved values of all CSS properties of an element, after applying active stylesheets and resolving any computation those values may contain.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] The returned object can be used to inspect the element's styles — including those set inline, using a `<style>` element, or via an external stylesheet.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] Since the object is read-only, you can't use it to set an element's styles.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] However, because it is "live", if you update the element styles using another API (such as `HTMLElement.style`), the returned object will be updated with the corresponding resolved value.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] The distinction that the object contains resolved values is important.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] For most properties, in particular those that don't depend on layout, such as `display`, `font-size`, or `line-height`, the resolved value is the computed value.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] For properties that depend on layout, the used value may differ slightly from the computed value, and this is what is returned as the resolved value.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] For an animating property value, it will be the computed value at the current point in the animation.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] The returned object has dash-named and corresponding camel-case named properties for **all** CSS properties supported by the browser, including both shorthand and longhand properties.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] Shorthand CSS properties of the element are expanded to their corresponding long-form properties.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] Note that the returned object is the same type as the object returned from the element's `style` property.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] However, the `element.style` object can also be used to **set** styles on that element, and returns just the inline styles or those set via JavaScript.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] For compatibility reasons, serialized color values specified using the traditional sRGB color space are expressed as `rgb()` colors if the alpha channel value is exactly `1`, and `rgba()` colors otherwise.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] The legacy syntax with commas is used, with commas as separators (for example `rgb(255, 0, 0)`).
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] For other color spaces the values are serialized using the corresponding functional expressions: `lab()`, `lch()` `oklab()`, `oklch()`, `color()`.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] In this example, we style a `<p>` element, then retrieve those styles using `getComputedStyle()`, and print them into the text content of the `<p>`.
[src:css-object-model/getcomputedstyle] `getComputedStyle()` can pull style info from pseudo-elements, such as `::after`, `::before`, `::marker`, or `::line-marker`.
